OFFICIAL

IPC: Sockets

  • Inter-process Communication using sockets:
    • works even across a network
  • using the loopback adapter, you can use sockets to communicate between process on the same machine
    • uses localhost (127.0.0.1)
    • client
    • server

OFFICIAL

Purposes of IPC sockets

  • Data sharing- allows multiple process for sharing data.
  • Synchronization- synchronizing access of shared resources, ensuring data integrity.
  • Modularity- supports module design.
  • Resource management- manages utilization of resources efficiently.
  • Scalability- allows different services or applications to interact, facilitating scalability.

OFFICIAL

Python Socket Library

  • socket()- create a new socket.
  • bind()- associates the socket to a specific address and port.
  • listen()- starts listening for incoming connections.
  • accept()- accepts a connection from a client and returns a new socket for communication.
  • connect()- Establishes a connection to a remote server.
  • send()- Sends data through the socket.
  • recv()- Receives data from the socket.
  • close()- Closes the socket connection.

import socket

QUEUE_SIZE = 5

def server():

serv = socket.socket(

socket.AF_INET,

socket.SOCK_STREAM)

serv.bind(('', 5000))

serv.listen(QUEUE_SIZE)

# always listen for connections

while True:

conn, addr = serv.accept()

print(f’Cntn: {addr}')

from_client = ‘’

# Always listen for data

# Always listen for data

while True:

data = conn.recv(4096)

# end of data

if not data:

break

from_client += data.decode()

print(from_client)

conn.send(

"You are LEGEND<br>“.encode())

conn.close()

print('client disconnected')

if __name__ == '__main__':

server()

OFFICIAL

Client

import socket

def client():

# Create client socket (AF_INET => IP, SOCK_STREAM => TCP)

sock = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)

sock.connect(('127.0.0.1', 5000))

sock.send("I am LEGEND<br>".encode())

from_server = sock.recv(4096)

sock.close()

print(from_server.decode())

if __name__ == '__main__':

client()

OFFICIAL

Threading

import socket

Import threading

QUEUE_SIZE = 5

def server():

serv = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)

serv.bind(('', 5000))

serv.listen(QUEUE_SIZE)

print(“Server is listening on port 5000…”)

# always listen for connections

while True:

conn, addr = serv.accept()

print(f’Cntn: {addr}')

from_client = ‘’

# Always listen for data

while True:

data = conn.recv(4096)

# end of data

if not data:

break

from_client += data.decode()

print(from_client)

conn.send("You are LEGEND<br>“.encode())

conn.close()

print('client disconnected')

def client():

# Give server a moment to start

import time

time.sleep(1)

sock = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)

sock.connect(('127.0.0.1', 5000))

sock.send("I am LEGEND<br>".encode())

from_server = sock.recv(4096)

sock.close()

print(from_server.decode())

if __name__ == '__main__’:

# Start the server in a separate thread

server_thread = threading.Thread(target=server, daemon=True)

server_Thread.start()

# Run the client

client()
